  "meta-ads-cpm-too-high": {
    title: "Your Meta Ads CPM Is Too High. Here Are the 7 Real Reasons Why.",
    description: "High CPM on Meta Ads isn't random — it has specific, diagnosable causes. This is the breakdown of every reason CPM rises, with the exact fix for each one.",
    category: "Performance",
    readTime: "7 min",
    date: "March 2026",
    author: "AdBrief Team",
    authorRole: "Performance Intelligence",
    keywords: ["meta ads cpm high", "facebook ads cpm too high", "why is my cpm so high meta", "reduce cpm facebook ads", "meta ads cpm increase", "lower cpm meta ads"],
    content: [
      "## CPM Is a Symptom, Not a Problem",
      "When CPM spikes, the instinct is to blame the platform — 'Meta is getting more expensive.' Sometimes that's true. Most of the time it isn't. CPM is a signal from the algorithm about how efficiently it can deliver your ads to your target audience. When CPM rises, the algorithm is telling you something specific.",
      "Here are the 7 real reasons CPM rises on Meta, in order of frequency.",
      "## Reason 1: Creative Fatigue (Most Common)",
      "When your creative loses its novelty with the target audience, Meta's algorithm has to work harder to find people willing to engage. Working harder means paying more — CPM rises.",
      "Signal: CPM rising while CTR falling. Frequency above 2.5 on prospecting campaigns. Hook rate declining week-over-week.",
      "Fix: refresh creative. Not a new campaign, not new targeting — new creative in the existing ad set. Give the algorithm fresh material to work with.",
      "## Reason 2: Audience Exhaustion",
      "Distinct from creative fatigue: your targeting has reached the same people too many times regardless of the creative. The algorithm has to reach deeper into the audience, where people are less likely to engage — so it charges more.",
      "Signal: frequency rising across all creatives in an ad set simultaneously. Reach declining even with stable spend. Cost per result rising across all variations.",
      "Fix: expand targeting, introduce a new lookalike seed audience, or temporarily pause and let the audience reset.",
      "## Reason 3: Low Relevance Score",
      "Meta rewards ads that generate engagement with lower CPMs. An ad that people interact with positively (likes, shares, saves, clicks) gets a better delivery discount. An ad that people hide or report gets penalized with higher CPM.",
      "Signal: low engagement rate relative to CTR. Comments that are negative or confused. High hide/report rate (visible in Ad Relevance Diagnostics).",
      "Fix: improve the creative-audience match. The most common cause is targeting an audience that's too broad for a specific-angle ad.",
      "## Reason 4: Seasonal Competition",
      "Q4, Valentine's Day, Black Friday, back-to-school — every brand is competing for the same impressions simultaneously. Supply (ad inventory) stays roughly constant while demand spikes. CPM rises for everyone.",
      "Signal: CPM rising across all campaigns simultaneously, not just one campaign. Industry benchmarks also rising. No changes made to your account that correlate with the timing.",
      "Fix: you can't fix seasonal competition. You can prepare for it with stronger creative, higher bids, and reduced targeting constraints. Or intentionally reduce spend during peak competition windows.",
      "## Reason 5: Overly Narrow Targeting",
      "The smaller your target audience, the fewer impressions are available, the more you pay for each one. An audience of 50,000 people will always have higher CPM than an audience of 5 million — all else being equal.",
      "Signal: reach consistently lower than 50% of audience size. Frequency rising faster than expected. Delivery falling below budget even with competitive bids.",
      "Fix: expand targeting. Remove overly restrictive interest layers. Test broader audiences with stronger creative instead of narrow audiences with weak creative.",
      "## Reason 6: Bid Strategy Mismatch",
      "Cost cap and bid cap strategies can artificially suppress delivery when set too conservatively — and when the algorithm struggles to spend your budget at the cap, it sometimes raises effective CPM by reducing delivery efficiency.",
      "Signal: underspending relative to budget. Irregular delivery patterns. Low impression volume despite reasonable audience size.",
      "Fix: test highest volume (no bid cap) in a new campaign to establish a CPM baseline. If highest volume CPM is lower than your current strategy's CPM, your bid cap is too restrictive.",
      "## Reason 7: Account Quality Issues",
      "Meta scores accounts on overall quality based on the feedback and engagement signals across all their ads. An account with a history of disapprovals, user hides, or policy violations has a lower account quality score — and pays higher CPM across the board.",
      "Signal: CPM rising across all campaigns simultaneously without any of the other signals present. Ad relevance diagnostics showing 'below average' ratings.",
      "Fix: address any active policy flags. Pause underperforming ads with high negative feedback rates. Build account quality back over 2-4 weeks of clean activity.",
      "## Diagnosing Your CPM Problem Faster",
      "Running through all 7 of these reasons manually takes time. AdBrief connects to your Meta Ads account and can identify which of these factors is driving your CPM issue in a single conversation. Ask 'Why is my CPM rising?' and get a specific answer based on your actual account data — not a generic checklist.",
      "Try AdBrief free for 1 day on any plan. Diagnose your CPM problem in under 10 minutes.",
    ],
  },

